ne:** April–June (for following year).\n- **Key:** High GRE required for most STEM; strong research/community work.\n\n### 6. **MEXT Scholarship (Japan)**\n- **Who:** Any field; university recommendation or embassy track.\n- **Coverage:** Full tuition, monthly stipend (~¥143,000), travel.\n- **Deadline:** Embassy track: April–May; University track varies.\n- **Key:** Strong academic record; some require JLPT N2 or English.\n\n### 7. **Chinese Government Scholarship (CSC)**\n- **Who:** Any field; through Chinese universities.\n- **Coverage:** Full tuition, accommodation, stipend (~¥3,000/month), medical insurance.\n- **Deadline:** Typically February–April.\n- **Key:** Apply to multiple	0	2026-06-08 07:01:22.937623+00	\N	2026-06-09 07:01:21.803+00
dc1f683c-8fb2-4c55-bce8-090c695c5604	55470865bab5c195d919ad3df48a0b0ff463be27fdfbe2727ff33f08153d4051	deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash	Hi iam currently completed my bsc in cse form bd with cgpa 3.4 but i wanna go for musters funding\nas its very competitive do you have  any suggestion for me how to prepare for and things to keep in my mind	Congratulations on completing your BSc in CSE! A 3.4 CGPA is solid — competitive enough for many funded Master's programs, especially if you strengthen other parts of your profile. Here’s a practical roadmap:\n\n## 🎯 Key Scholarships to Target\n\n- **DAAD (Germany)** – Full funding for CSE-related programs like "ICT for Development" or "Data Engineering" at German universities. No strict CGPA cutoff, but strong academic record + work/research experience helps.\n- **Erasmus Mundus Joint Master’s (EU)** – Multiple scholarships with living allowance. Programs like "Big Data Management & Analytics" or "Security & Cloud Computing" are CSE-friendly. Competitive, but 3.4 is fine if you have good motivation letters.\n- **Commonwealth Scholarships (UK)** – For developing countries (Bangladesh is eligible). Requires 2–3 years of work experience. Start building that now.\n- **Fulbright (USA)** – Fully funded Master's + tuition waiver. Extremely competitive, but CSE + strong research or leadership can compensate.\n- **Swiss Government Excellence Scholarships** – For Master's at ETH Zurich or EPFL (highly competitive). Requires strong research background.\n\n## 📌 Your Preparation Checklist\n\n1. **Research experience** – Publish 1–2 conference papers, even in local or low-tier venues. Real projects on GitHub with clear documentation.\n2. **Standardized tests** –  \n   - **IELTS/TOEFL**: Aim for 7.0+ (IELTS) or 100+ (TOEFL).  \n   - **GRE**: Not required for most EU/UK scholarships, but helps for US (Fulbright, some US programs). Target 320+.\n3. **Strong SOP & LORs** – Each scholarship needs a tailored Statement of Purpose linking your past projects to the specific program. Get 2-3 letters from professors who supervised your thesis or research.\n4. **Work experience** – If possible, work for 1–2 years as a junior developer, research assistant, or in a relevant role. Commonwealth explicitly prefers applicants with work experience.\n5. **Apply to multiple tiers** – Aim for 5–8 programs: 2–3 stretch (ETH, Fulbright), 3–4 realistic (DAAD, Erasmus Mundus, specific German universities), 2–3 safe (self-funded or partial scholarships from universities).\n\n## 💡 Mindset Shift\n\n- A 3.4 CGPA is a starting point, not a barrier. Most scholarship committees evaluate your **potential, research fit, and motivation** more than a decimal difference.\n- Start **one year ahead** of deadlines. Most applications open 10–12 months before program start.\n- Network with alumni from your university who got these scholarships. They can review your SOP and give insider tips.\n\nYou have a fair shot! Want me to break	0	2026-06-08 13:27:16.718196+00	\N	2026-06-09 13:27:16.562+00
